Self-test — you can't test an HMAC endpoint without producing a real signature. Two curls after go build ./... passes and the service is up:
bash# 1. Forged request → expect 401
curl -i -X POST localhost:8082/webhooks/razorpay \
  -H 'X-Razorpay-Signature: deadbeef' \
  --data-binary '{"event":"payment.captured"}'

# 2. Validly signed request → expect 200 + your log line
BODY='{"event":"payment.captured"}'
SIG=$(printf '%s' "$BODY" | openssl dgst -sha256 -hmac "$RAZORPAY_WEBHOOK_SECRET" -r | cut -d' ' -f1)
curl -i -X POST localhost:8082/webhooks/razorpay \
  -H "X-Razorpay-Signature: $SIG" \
  --data-binary "$BODY"
That second curl is you being Razorpay — same math, same secret. If it 401s, your middleware and openssl disagree about the bytes (usually a stray newline — hence printf, not echo).
